
	
	
	


<h1 class="western" align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><font color="#3399ff"><span style="font-weight: normal">Operating
System (P</span></font><font color="#3399ff"><span style="font-weight: normal">2</span></font><font color="#3399ff"><span style="font-weight: normal">)</span></font></font></h1>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Operating
systems are the software that makes you use the computer more easily.
They are the interface between machine and man. The OS manages all
the hardware in the computer telling the processor what to do.
Without an operating system it would be impossible to use a computer,
they'd be useless.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Nowadays it
is not common, but sometime ago there were some different
characteristics in the operating systems. Such as single-user OS
(only has one user in the computer), single-tasking which only runs
one task at a time. There were also the command line operating
system, that consisted in a console form where you had to type
commands manually to use the computer, ex.: to create a folder in an
Ubuntu (Linux) console distribution you would have to type:</font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><img src="data:image/png;base64," name="Image4" align="left" width="568" height="36" border="0">
<br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Today there
are mainly three computer OSs in the market: Windows, MAC OS and
Linux (all of them are based on GUI). Depending on which system you
are using it may give you different functions and different methods
of doing things.  Also according to your OS the drivers which are the
software that tells the computer how to deal with a specific
component (such as GPU or a USB Flash Drive) may be different, and
some may not be available. </font>
</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal"><font color="#3399ff">OS
Services and Features</font></h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Operating
Systems come with different functionalities, but there are some
important and common ones. Those are the ones I’m going to explain
and compare if possible.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><b>Personalizatio</b><b>n
– </b>Because of people’s
different preferences the Operating Systems give the option to be
customized, which may allow you to change time, wallpaper, installed
software, sometimes even the OS theme. These personalization
functions are available since the OS installation where you can give
the computer a name, create your user, set a password, etc.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><b>File
Management –</b> File management consists in the ability to create,
rename, copy, paste, move, share and delete files and folders. This
is one of the basic functionalities of the Operating System and it is
included in all of the 3 OSs cited above.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><b>Peripheral
Management – </b>External
peripherals are generally used to control or expand the machine’s
capability, such as expanding memory (Pen Drives), typing (Keyboard)
or moving the cursor (Mouse/Trackpad). Some devices need special
attention, because some of them must require a software to tell the
computer how to deal with the device. These software are called
<b>drivers</b>. On Windows
(most recent versions) drivers are installed when the new device is
connected to the machine. On Ubuntu
and Mac OSX the
drivers for all the compatible devices are
included in
it's
kernel.</font></p>
<h1 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal; page-break-before: auto; page-break-after: auto">
<font color="#3399ff"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">OS
comparison (M1)</font></font></h1>
<p align="justify"><font color="#000000"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	</font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Because
of the many different functionalities of the OSs a comparison might
be good to clarify the different advantages and disadvantages of
each. But before the comparison a quick brief about each of the three
cited above.</font></font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal">Windows</h2>
<p align="justify">	Windows is the
most popular OS between standard users in the whole world. It is a
GUI OS that is compatible with most part of the available software in
the market, has many
different versions and
restrict functions,
doesn't have a fixed release date (new versions are
announced suddenly).
Because of its popularity,
most part of the viruses are made for it, so it needs to be
constantly scanned, and also because of the storage type (NTFS) it
needs to be cleaned and defragmented very often.</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h1 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal">Mac
OSX</h1>
<p align="justify">	OSX is probably
the most recommended OS for producing audio-visual stuff, it has more
available software than Linux and less than Windows. It has one of
the most polished GUI in the market and offers more personalization
options than Windows. It is restricted to Mac machines and some
updates require extra tax or new hardware, because
of that,  many people choose to
use other OSs (taking
the fact that Mac machines
are very expensive).</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h1 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal">Ubuntu
15.10 (Linux)</h1>
<p align="justify">	Ubuntu
is a free and open-source OS that offers security, performance and
stability to the user. Like OSX and Windows it is a GUI based OS and
has many different “Flavours”
- which basically means a different interface. There
are no “pro” or “student” versions nor
restricted features on Ubuntu. Because it is open-source bug fixes
come up quickly either officially or not. It has one of the biggest
active support community in the web and it has the greatest range of
software between the other Linux distributions.</p>

<h1 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal"><font color="#3399ff">Security
and Reliability</font></h1>
<h2 class="western" align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Windows
10</font></h2>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Windows is
the most used PC OS in the world, and is also the most unstable and
insecure. It has many viruses and failures, and constantly crashes
(the well known “blue screen of the death”). One of the reasons
that makes it the most used OS is the software compatibility. Almost
all the programs were made to run on Windows. It might be quite
expensive, and require a good piece of hardware.</font></p>
<h3 class="western" align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Software:</font></h3>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Windows has
many different defensive software available to be downloaded for free
and paid. It has also its own software such as Windows Firewall and
Windows Defender (that are very famous for doing nothing).</font></p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	For cleaning
up the disk there are many different software for windows including
its own tool that can be found in the Control Panel (it is necessary
to be used after some days otherwise you will lose performance).</font></p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Mac
OSX and Ubuntu 15.10 (Linux)</font></h2>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	Mac and
Linux are together in this topic because they are very much the same
thing when talking about stability and security, mainly because they
deal with packages installations in a different and more secure way.
Both are based on Unix and are very stable even in its new releases
(unlike the last releases of Windows).</font></p>
<h3 class="western" align="justify">      <font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Software:</font></h3>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	There are
defensive software available to be installed on both but it is really
not necessary. Both have their own firewall, and because of the more
secure way that they deal with package installations they make having
an anti-virus software an option – not needed by the way.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">	The disk
storage type on both are much better than NTFS (used on Windows)
because they make cleaning and defragging unnecessary – Mac OSX
uses HFX and Linux uses Ext4.</font></p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h1 class="western" align="justify" style="font-weight: normal"><font color="#3399ff">Improving
System Performance (D1)</font></h1>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify">	Virus protection:</h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify">	Installing a virus protection software is the
best choice you make when you are running Windows. It will protect
your system against threads and might prevent unwanted software from
being installed in you machine. If you are running Ubuntu or OS X you
don’t need an antivirus, it’s up to you installing one or not.
But keep in mind that it might slow down your OS.</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify">	Browser history and cookies
removal:</h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify">	This is a procedure that old machine users might
want to do. Removing the browsing history  reduces the range of
completion in the search bar, preferences for ads and erases the
history of most visited pages which all together is going to give
your web browser a little boost in openning time and general use
performance. Cookies in general store passwords and usernames to
autocomplete them when you login in some pages but, after some time
it stores too many usernames and passwords, it tries to use passwords
from other accounts and some times might be a bit annoying. Removing
them improves some pages opening delay, annoying password/username
confusion but in the other hand it will delete all your saved
passwords.</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify">	Disk defragmentation:</h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify">	If you are an SSD and/or Ubuntu/OS X user please
skip this step as you either don’t need or can’t do this step
(its unnecessary because of the storage type EXT4 or HFX and because
SSDs are not defragmentable). If you are a Windows + HD user then you
must do this step at least twice a month. Defragging a disk removes
the spaces between data written on it making read and write much
faster, it also reorganizes the disk removing corrupted files and
moving them in a way that they are written as complete (all in
sequence) as possible.</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify">	Drive formatting:</h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify">	During the OS installation and even after you can
split your storage device in two (or more) leaving the OS
installation in the first partition and personal files such as
documents and photos in the second one. By doing it your OS booting
will get faster as there are less files in the installation partition
and also reduce the time that opening programs take. In case you
format your installation you can leave the second partition intact
and only reinstall the OS in the first partition, then you didn’t
even have to upload all your files to the cloud or make a physical
backup (which by the way is totally recommended).</p>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<h2 class="western" align="justify">	Using a firewall:</h2>
<p align="justify"><br>
<br>

</p>
<p align="justify">	Using a firewall doesn’t increase your system
performance directly, but it does a lot to keep it as it is by
protecting all the internet connection ports on your machine it
prevents loads of unwanted software from being installed, files from
being downloaded and also makes it unnecessary to upgrade you
antivirus to a paid version that includes firewall protection.</p>
